        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "1. `High`: Direct-peer discovery still treats an unbound identity proof plus any `200 OK` submit as “direct delivery,” so a relay attacker can blackhole Tier 1 traffic. The discovery controller explicitly notes that the identity challenge is not channel-bound to the responder endpoint, then immediately registers the discovered URL as a direct peer ([controller.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs#L380), [controller.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs#L495)). In the direct tier, the coordinator returns success on the first successful POST regardless of whether the receipt was missing or invalid ([coordinator.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/coordinator.rs#L585), [delivery.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/delivery.rs#L376)). That means an attacker who relays the identity challenge to the real contact can get registered as the direct peer and then win Tier 1 by accepting the POST without proving recipient possession.\n\n2. `Medium`: The branch makes `/api/v1/identity` public on the standalone node even when HTTP auth is configured, and it is not rate-limited. The router now puts `GET /api/v1/identity` outside the auth middleware ([api.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/src/api.rs#L93)), while the handler signs arbitrary 32-byte challenges on demand ([api.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/node/src/api.rs#L878)). That broadens every authenticated mailbox node into a public signature oracle / identity-presence probe for anyone who can guess candidate keys, which is a real trust-boundary expansion from the previous authenticated-only surface.\n\n3. `Medium`: mDNS advertisement leaks the local hostname directly into the service instance and advertised host FQDN. The backend builds the visible instance name as `\"{hostname}-{pid}\"` and publishes `\"{hostname}.local.\"` as the host ([mdns_sd.rs](/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-discovery/src/mdns_sd.rs#L153)). That exposes device or user-identifying metadata on the LAN independently of the pseudonymous routing key in TXT, which is a privacy regression in the discovery design rather than just cosmetic naming.\n\n<oai-mem-citation>\n<citation_entries>\nMEMORY.md:87-91|note=[used quick memory pass only for local skill/capability discovery guidance before review]\n</citation_entries>\n<rollout_ids>\n</rollout_ids>\n</oai-mem-citation>",
