          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a163********6983</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********WTSG</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/a163650dde18b6983.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Spec review: transport caps\" completed</summary>\n<result>I now have a complete picture. Here is the review.\n\n---\n\n## Spec Review: Transport Capabilities\n\n### [INFO] Booleans vs Bitflags — Documented Deviation\n**Spec reference:** Plan, \"Transport Capability Model\" section\n**Finding:** The plan specifies `bitflags::bitflags! { pub struct TargetCapabilities: u8 { ... } }`. The implementation uses a plain struct with four `bool` fields instead. This is documented inline at `target.rs:234-235`:\n\n> *\"This is local configuration, not wire data -- plain booleans are clearer than bitflags for flags that are checked individually.\"*\n\nThe `#[allow(clippy::struct_excessive_bools)]` annotation further acknowledges the choice. The semantic coverage is identical: `send`, `fetch`, `quorum_credit`, `replicate` map 1:1 to the plan's `SEND`, `FETCH`, `QUORUM_CREDIT`, `REPLICATE`.\n**Status:** Documented deviation (acceptable)\n\n---\n\n### [MEDIUM] Stable defaults: `replicate: false` deviates from plan\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 2: \"Stable defaults: `SEND | FETCH | QUORUM_CREDIT | REPLICATE`\"; Plan, \"Transport Capability Model\" table: Configured mailbox node = `SEND | FETCH | QUORUM_CREDIT | REPLICATE`\n**Finding:** `TargetCapabilities::stable_defaults()` at `target.rs:251-257` sets `replicate: false`. The plan explicitly says stable defaults should include `REPLICATE`. This means configured mailbox nodes do not advertise replication capability by default.\n\nThere is currently no code anywhere in the coordinator that filters by `replicate`, so the flag has zero enforcement points today. However, the plan's intent was to have the flag set so that future replication logic would work without a config migration.\n**Status:** Deviation -- stable defaults omit `REPLICATE` contrary to the plan's \"all flags set\" specification.\n\n---\n\n### [PASS] `fetch_once()` filters by FETCH capability\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Enforcement points: \"`TransportPool::fetch_once()` ... filter to targets with `FETCH` capability\"\n**Finding:** `pool.rs:649-659`, `fetch_from_targets()` filters targets with `.filter(|t| t.config().capabilities.fetch)`. The `fetch_once()` method delegates to `fetch_from_targets()`. Test `test_fetch_skips_non_fetchable_targets` at `pool.rs:807-825` verifies that an ephemeral-only pool returns \"No fetchable targets\".\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [PASS] `submit_to_quorum_targets()` filters by QUORUM_CREDIT\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Enforcement points: \"`submit_to_quorum_targets()`: filter to targets with `QUORUM_CREDIT`\"\n**Finding:** `coordinator.rs:645-650` filters HTTP targets with `pool.targets_where(|c| c.quorum_credit)`. The `quorum_target_count()` and `quorum_target_ids()` methods use the same filter. Tests `test_quorum_target_count_uses_capabilities` and `test_quorum_target_ids_uses_capabilities` verify this.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [LOW] Replication has no enforcement point\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Enforcement points: \"Replication: filter to targets with `REPLICATE`\"\n**Finding:** There is no code in the coordinator or pool that filters by `capabilities.replicate`. The `replicate` field exists in `TargetCapabilities` but is never read anywhere in the codebase. This is consistent with the fact that replication is not yet implemented, but the plan expected an enforcement point to exist.\n**Status:** Partial -- field exists, enforcement deferred. Acceptable if replication itself is out-of-scope for v0.4.\n\n---\n\n### [MEDIUM] Coordinator mutation API: `update_http_target()` is `replace_http_target()`\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Coordinator mutation API: \"`add_http_target()`, `remove_http_target()`, `update_http_target(id, url)`\"\n**Finding:** The coordinator implements `add_http_target()`, `remove_http_target()`, and `replace_http_target(old_id, new_target: HttpTarget)` at `coordinator.rs:178-205`. The plan specifies `update_http_target(id, url)` which takes a URL; the implementation takes a full `HttpTarget` object and has different semantics (atomic remove+add under single lock, upsert behavior). The naming changed from `update_` to `replace_`.\n\nThis is arguably a better API (atomic swap prevents races where neither old nor new target exists), but it is a deviation from the plan's interface spec.\n**Status:** Deviation -- different name and signature, but improved semantics.\n\n---\n\n### [HIGH] `TransportRegistry` NOT converted to read-only view\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 2: \"Convert `TransportRegistry` to a read-only view: Remove `add_http_target()` and other mutation methods.\"\n**Finding:** `TransportRegistry` at `registry.rs` still has `pub async fn add_http_target()` and retains `with_composite()`. The plan requires removing mutation methods and replacing `with_composite()` with `with_coordinator()`. Neither change has been made.\n\nThis means there are two write authorities for target management: the coordinator's mutation API and the registry's own `add_http_target()`. This is the \"dual-authority problem\" (ARCH-6) that the plan was explicitly designed to eliminate.\n**Status:** Deviation -- registry still has mutation methods, violating single-write-authority invariant.\n\n---\n\n### [HIGH] `MessageReceiver` NOT deprecated\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Chunk 2: \"Deprecate `MessageReceiver` -- superseded by `TransportCoordinator::subscribe()`\"\n**Finding:** `MessageReceiver` at `receiver.rs` is still fully present, exported from `lib.rs:44` as a public type, and has no `#[deprecated]` attribute. The plan requires deprecation (and removal if no other consumers exist).\n\n`lib.rs:44`: `pub use receiver::{MessageReceiver, ReceiverConfig, ReceiverHandle};`\n**Status:** Deviation -- `MessageReceiver` is still active, not deprecated.\n\n---\n\n### [PASS] `spawn_http_receiver()` delegates FETCH filtering to pool\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Enforcement points: \"`TransportCoordinator::spawn_http_receiver()`: filter to targets with `FETCH` capability\"\n**Finding:** `spawn_http_receiver()` calls `pool.fetch_once()` which internally calls `fetch_from_targets()`, which filters by `capabilities.fetch`. The coordinator does not need its own filter -- it correctly delegates.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [PASS] Invariant tests for QUORUM_CREDIT\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Test Plan: \"target without `QUORUM_CREDIT` never counted toward quorum\"\n**Finding:** `test_quorum_target_count_uses_capabilities` at `coordinator.rs:1187-1214` creates stable (has QUORUM_CREDIT), ephemeral (no QUORUM_CREDIT), and ephemeral-with-override targets, then asserts only the two with `quorum_credit: true` are counted. `test_quorum_target_ids_uses_capabilities` at `coordinator.rs:1218-1239` verifies the ephemeral target's ID is excluded.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n### [PASS] Invariant tests for FETCH filtering\n**Spec reference:** Plan, Test Plan: \"target without `FETCH` never polled\"\n**Finding:** `test_fetch_skips_non_fetchable_targets` at `pool.rs:807-825` verifies that a pool with only an ephemeral target (no FETCH) returns a \"No fetchable targets\" error. `test_fetch_includes_fetchable_targets` at `pool.rs:828-849` verifies that a stable target (with FETCH) is attempted.\n**Status:** Compliant\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\n| # | Severity | Finding | Status |\n|---|----------|---------|--------|\n| 1 | INFO | Booleans instead of bitflags | Documented deviation |\n| 2 | MEDIUM | `stable_defaults()` has `replicate: false` | Deviation |\n| 3 | PASS | `fetch_once()` filters by FETCH | Compliant |\n| 4 | PASS | `submit_to_quorum_targets()` filters by QUORUM_CREDIT | Compliant |\n| 5 | LOW | No REPLICATE enforcement point | Partial (acceptable for v0.4) |\n| 6 | MEDIUM | `update_http_target` became `replace_http_target` | Deviation (improved) |\n| 7 | HIGH | `TransportRegistry` still has mutation methods | Deviation |\n| 8 | HIGH | `MessageReceiver` not deprecated | Deviation |\n| 9 | PASS | `spawn_http_receiver()` FETCH delegation | Compliant |\n| 10 | PASS | Quorum invariant tests | Compliant |\n| 11 | PASS | Fetch invariant tests | Compliant |\n\n**Key files reviewed:**\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/target.rs`\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/pool.rs`\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/coordinator.rs`\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/lib.rs`\n- `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/crates/reme-transport/src/registry.rs`\n\n**Two HIGH findings require attention:** The registry still has mutation methods (dual-authority risk), and `MessageReceiver` has not been deprecated. Both were explicitly called out in the plan as required changes for Chunk 2. The `replicate: false` default for stable targets (finding #2) is worth a deliberate decision -- if this is intentional to avoid premature commitment, it should be documented in a code comment.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>68917</total_tokens><tool_uses>18</tool_uses><duration_ms>102775</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /tmp/claude-1000/-home-leon0399-Projects-reme/36b495c0-95b9-49fc-8523-b911e74011a9/tasks/a163650dde18b6983.output",
