he \"why\" (LAN discovery needs unauthenticated identity, monitoring needs unauthenticated health). No simplification needed.\n\n**One observation:** `DefaultBodyLimit::max(MAX_BODY_SIZE)` is only on `auth_routes`. The `get_identity` endpoint accepts a query parameter (not body), and `health_check` has no body, so this is correct in practice. However, if a future public route accepts a body, it would silently lack the limit. This is not a code change — just something to note in a comment or keep in mind.\n\n---\n\n### 5. `apps/node/src/api.rs` lines 871-942 — Identity handler is reasonable but has one unnecessary intermediate\n\n**Current (lines 910-914):**\n```rust\nlet identity = identity.clone();\n\nlet challenge: [u8; 32] = challenge.try_into().expect(\"validated above\");\nlet result = tokio::task::spawn_blocking(move || {\n```\n\n**Issue:** The `identity.clone()` on line 911 clones the `Arc` to move into the closure. The original `identity` is a reference from `&state.identity`. This is fine and necessary — no simplification here.\n\nThe `challenge.try_into().expect(\"validated above\")` on line 914 is also fine — the length check on line 897 guarantees this. Some codebases prefer to do the `try_into` immediately after validation and return a proper error instead of `expect`, but given that the length check is 3 lines above, this is acceptable.\n\n**Assessment:** The handler is well-structured. No meaningful simplification available.\n\n---\n\n### 6. `AGENTS.md` lines 55-66 — LAN Discovery section partially duplicates threat model and inline code\n\n**Current:** The AGENTS.md \"LAN Discovery\" section describes the operational flow (mDNS browsing, identity verification, SEND-only targets, `max_peers`). The threat model's sections 1, 3, and 6 cover the same mechanisms from a security perspective.\n\n**Assessment:** This is actually fine — AGENTS.md serves as a quick-reference for agents working on the code, while the threat model is a security analysis. The ove